A Roman bookkeeper has two ways of using the roman libary (in Ubuntu 16.04LTS).
One way is with the Python REPL.
The other is with a dedicated calculator program.
(what has to be installed?)

Perform addition and subtraction in Python REPL.

    doric@column:~/pillar/kata-roman-numeral-calculator$ python3
    Python 3.5.2 (default, Sep 14 2017, 22:51:06) 
    [GCC 5.4.0 20160609] on linux
    Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
    >>> from roman import Roman
    >>> Roman('XXIV') + Roman('XIX')
    Roman('XLIII')
    >>> _ + Roman('VI')
    Roman('XLIX')
    >>> _ + Roman('II')
    Roman('LI')
    >>> s = _
    >>> s + s
    Roman('CII')
    >>> s - Roman('II')
    Roman('XLIX')
    >>> s - Roman('II') - Roman('L')
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
      File "/home/jep/pillar/kata-roman-numeral-calculator/roman.py", line 93, in __sub__
        raise OverflowError
    OverflowError
    >>> s - Roman('II') - Roman('XL')
    Roman('IX')
    >>> Roman('X') - Roman('IX')
    Roman('I')
    >>> s = Roman('X')
    >>> s
    Roman('X')
    >>> s -= Roman('I')
    >>> s
    Roman('IX')
    >>> s += Roman('M')
    >>> s
    Roman('MIX')
    >>> s -= Roman('MM')
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
      File "/home/jep/pillar/kata-roman-numeral-calculator/roman.py", line 93, in __sub__
        raise OverflowError
    OverflowError
    >>> s
    Roman('MIX')
    >>> 
    doric@column:~/pillar/kata-roman-numeral-calculator$ 

To run pytest for development, run the following on Ubuntu.

    sudo apt-get update
    sudo apt-get install -y python3-venv
    python3 -m venv env
    source env/bin/activate
    pip install -r requirements-dev.txt
    py.test -f .
